🧩 Step 2 — To see only Node.js processes
If you’re running React (which uses Node), check this:

bash
Copy code
ps aux | grep node
You’ll get details like:

yaml
Copy code
bhopal_redcross  2314  2.3  8.1 1287368 165232 ? Sl 11:20 0:03 node start.js
🧩 Step 3 — To see the exact folder each process is using
Run:

bash
Copy code
lsof -p <PID> | grep bbiq_react
Replace <PID> with the process ID from step 1 (for example 2314).

That will show all files that process has open in your bbiq_react folder.

🧩 Step 4 — (Optional) Kill the running React process
If you find a running React dev server and want to stop it:

bash
Copy code
kill -9 <PID>
Example:

bash
Copy code
kill -9 2314
🧩 Step 5 — If you’re not sure which port it’s using
React usually runs on port 3000 or another one.
To see all ports in use by your user:

bash
Copy code
sudo lsof -i -P -n | grep LISTEN
To filter only Node.js:

bash
Copy code
sudo lsof -i -P -n | grep node








